<h2><a id="What-is-NPS" style="pointer-events: none; cursor: default; color: #000 !important;" href="#">What is NPSÂ®?</a></h2>
NPSÂ® stands for Net Promoter ScoreÂ®. It is an index that ranges from -100 to 100 which indicates how willing customers would be to recommend your business to others. It is considered as an approximate measure of a businessâ€™s ability to win and retain customer loyalty.
<h3><i>How is NPSÂ® defined?</i></h3>
Net Promoter ScoreÂ® focuses on the fair treatment of customers and employees. Unlike traditional accounting that focuses on short-term business profits, NPSÂ® looks at the long-term picture. It focuses on how well-perceived a business is through the eyes of its customers and employees.

In simple terms, <a href="https://www.surveysensum.com/blog/what-is-net-promoter-score/">NPS</a> is the business equivalent of the lesson most of us were taught as children: <strong><i>Treat unto others as you would have them treat you.</i></strong>

<strong style="color: #0052cc;">Walt Bettinger, CEO of Charles Schwab</strong>, the global ï¬nancial services ï¬rm says so about Net Promoter ScoreÂ® â€”
<div style="font-size: 20px; position: relative; line-height: 1.3; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">

â€œThe beauty of Net Promoter is that it helps to simplify complex issues and helps people to make the right decisions. It makes people ask themselves: Is this the right thing to do for our customers, and is it economically appropriate for the ï¬rm?â€

</div>
From what Walt Bettinger has to say and from the overall use of NPSÂ® it can be deduced that the metric helps in meeting four major business requirements.
<h3>History of Net Promoter ScoreÂ®</h3>
NPSÂ® is the brainchild of three entities:
<ol>
 	<li><strong>Fred Reichheld</strong> - A business strategist with specialization in loyalty marketing and loyalty marketing model</li>
 	<li><strong>Bain &amp; Co</strong> - A global management consultancy that offers business consultancy services to public and private enterprises as well as for not-for-profits</li>
 	<li><strong>Satmetrix</strong> - An experience management software provider</li>
</ol>
The concept of NPSÂ® was first introduced to the world through an HBR article â€œ<a href="https://hbr.org/2003/12/the-one-number-you-need-to-grow">The One Number You Need to Grow</a>â€ authored by Fred Reichheld.

The <strong>idea of NPSÂ®</strong> was to replace the complicated process of running a typical customer satisfaction survey. Net Promoter Score Â® boils down the process to a single question, the responses to which can be used to determine customer satisfaction, and in some cases employee satisfaction as well.

<strong>That single question for NPSÂ® calculation is:</strong>
<div style="font-size: 20px; position: relative; line-height: 1.3; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">

â€œOn a scale of 0-10, how likely is it that you would recommend [your business name] to your friends, family or business associates?â€

</div>
<h2><a id="How-to-calculate-NPS" style="pointer-events: none; cursor: default; color: #000 !important;" href="#">How to calculate NPSÂ®?</a></h2>
NPSÂ® is calculated with the help of surveys soliciting feedback from customers. The respondents to these surveys are classified into three:
<ul>
 	<li><strong>Promoters</strong> - Customers/users who are extremely likely to recommend your product/service to others. They rank the highest in the NPSÂ® score â€” in the range of 9 to 10.</li>
 	<li><strong>Passives</strong> - Customers/users who are satisfied with your product/service. There is a high possibility for passives to switch loyalty to competitors for want of more features, pricing, service or any other factor. Their NPSÂ® rating is in the range of 7 to 8.</li>
 	<li><strong>Detractors</strong> - Customers/users who your product/service failed to impress. They may have been subject to poor quality products or services. In addition to switching loyalty, they might also resort to spreading negative remarks about your brand. They stand in the range of 0 to 6.</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

<strong>NPSÂ® is calculated by reducing % of detractors from % of promoters.</strong>

<img class="aligncenter wp-image-1777 size-full" src="https://www.surveysensum.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/promoters.jpg" alt="Net Promoter Score-calculation" width="1024" height="289" />
<em><strong>For example:</strong> if you have a 25% promoters, 55% passives and 20% detractors, your NPSÂ® calculation will be as below:</em>

<strong>25% promoters - 20% detractors = +5.</strong>

A positive NPSÂ® is a good indication. However, an Net Promoter Score Â® of 5 shows that there is plenty of room for improvement. Higher the NPSÂ®, better customer loyalty.
<div style="font-size: 20px; position: relative; line-height: 1.3; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 10px; margin: 15px 0;">

